$ python code/sp_demo.py --mode memory
============================================================
Activation Memory Scaling with Sequence Length
============================================================

Model config: hidden_dim=4096, layers=32, batch=1, FP16
------------------------------------------------------------
  Seq Length |    Per Layer |  Total (32L) | Note
------------------------------------------------------------
       2,048 |       0.02GB |        0.5GB | 
       4,096 |       0.03GB |        1.0GB | 
       8,192 |       0.06GB |        2.0GB | 
      16,384 |       0.12GB |        4.0GB | 
      32,768 |       0.25GB |        8.0GB | 
      65,536 |       0.50GB |       16.0GB | 
     131,072 |       1.00GB |       32.0GB | 
------------------------------------------------------------

Conclusion: Long sequences require sequence/context parallelism
to distribute activation memory across multiple GPUs.


$ torchrun --nproc_per_node=2 code/sp_demo.py --mode sequence_parallel
============================================================
Sequence Parallelism Demo
============================================================

World size: 2

Full sequence: (2, 8192, 1024)
Local chunk per GPU: (2, 4096, 1024)
Memory per GPU: 16.0 MB
Memory savings: 2x reduction vs full sequence
LayerNorm applied locally - no cross-GPU communication!
Each GPU processes its sequence chunk independently.
